What is it about Knuth's algorithm M that makes it unsuitable for use in a
crypto application?

I made a version that passes all my statistical tests with flying colors.
It uses 2 additive congruential generators, based on the irreducible
trinomials X**1201 + X**388 + 1, and Y**1423 + Y**228 + 1, respectively.

It uses high-order bits of Yn (call them j) to select some previous output
of X (call it V[j]).  It outputs the sum of 

	 circular-shifted V[j]
    plus the (as yet unused) low-order bits of Yn,

and then sets V[j] equal to Xn.

How would you cryptanalize this?

================= Begin Code Fragment

unsigned long
M()
{
#define BARREL(x) (((x)>>RSFTN)^((x)<<LSFTN))        /* Circular shift       */
#define Xn (*frntX += *rearX)                        /* Additive generator X */
#define Yn (*frntY += *rearY)                        /* Additive generator Y */

    register unsigned long Y = Yn;                   /* Generate Yn          */
    register unsigned long *V_sub_j = &(V[Y>>RSFTN]);/* Get ptr to V[j]      */
    register unsigned long old_V_sub_j = *V_sub_j;   /* Save old V[j]        */

    *V_sub_j = Xn;                                   /* Set V[j] <-- Xn      */
    UPDATE_PTRS_FOR_X;                               /* Update X's pointers  */
    UPDATE_PTRS_FOR_Y;                               /* Update Y's pointers  */

    return( BARREL(old_V_sub_j) + (Y & MASKN) );     /* Output the sum of    */
			        /* the circular-shifted old value of V[j]    */
			        /* plus the unused low-order bits of Yn      */
}

================= End Code Fragment

